3. Data Investigation¶

The data consists of computerized tomography (CT) images from 3 patient groups: * Healthy controls * Covid-19 patients * Patients with community-acquired pneumonia (CAP) Let's read the meta files to compute the number of patients in each group. After this step we will exclude CAP patients as the data size is very small.

4. Splitting¶

We will split the train, validation and test sets as 30% - 20% - 50%. At the end of this step you should have 4 lists named:

  • normal_val_file_list,
  • normal_test_file_list,
  • covid_val_file_list
  • covid_test_file_list

corresponding to the lists of filenames for validation and test sets in normal and covid group.
IMPORTANT: We must do the splitting on patient level to avoid data leakage. You can see the effect of splitting on data leakage in this article (check Table 4).

4. Dataset¶

To create a custom dataset, first we will write the necessary functions which are:

  • img_paths
  • read_and_resize_img
  • augmentation

I. Image Paths¶

You will write a function that takes data_dir and partition arguments and returns a shuffled list of normal and covid image paths within that partition. Random seed is not necessary.

In [ ]:
import random
def img_paths(data_dir, partition):
  ##### START OF YOUR CODE #####

  #Combine with the directory and partition.
  partition_paths = os.path.join(data_dir, partition)
  #Choose normal photos.
  normal_path = os.path.join(partition_paths, "normal")
  #Take the paths of normal photos.
  normal_img_paths = [os.path.join(normal_path, filename) for filename in os.listdir(normal_path)]
  #Choose covid photos.
  covid_path = os.path.join(partition_paths, "covid")
  #Take the paths of covid photos.
  covid_img_paths = [os.path.join(covid_path, filename) for filename in os.listdir(covid_path)]
  #Gather all paths (normal&covid)
  combined_path = normal_img_paths + covid_img_paths
  #Shuffle the images
  random.shuffle(combined_path)
  return combined_path

  ##### END OF YOUR CODE #####

II. Read and Resize Image¶

You will write read_and_resize_img function that takes path and image_size arguments. It will

  • reads the image path using Image module of PIL package
  • converts the image to grayscale
  • adds the channel dimension
  • normalize to [0, 1]
  • resizes if the size of the image is different than image_size.

Ex: read_and_resize_img(path="path/to/image/", image_size=256) should return a torch tensor with a size of (1, 256, 256).

In [ ]:
from PIL import Image
import torch
import torchvision.transforms as T


def read_and_resize_img(path, image_size):
  ##### START OF YOUR CODE #####
  #Open the path of the image.
  img = Image.open(path)
  #Convcert image to grayscale.
  img = img.convert('L')
  #Normalize to [0,1]
  transform = T.Compose([T.ToTensor()])
  img = transform(img)
  #Size Check
  if img.size(0) != image_size or img.size(1) != image_size or img.size(2) != image_size:
        img = T.functional.resize(img, image_size)
  return img
  ##### END OF YOUR CODE #####

III. Augmentation¶

There are various augmentation techniques but we need to make sure that these reflect the variations that we might encounter in real life. That is why we will use Torchio library which is specifically designed for radiology data. Take a look at the augmentation transforms in here. You will write a function that applies the following transforms with the desired probability:

  • Random Noise with p = .2
  • Random Bias Field with p = .2
  • Random Ghosting with p = .2
  • Random Spike with p = .2
  • Random Affine with the parameters of (degrees=10, scales=0., translation=0.)and p = .2

Your function should apply either one of these augmentations and it should apply transformation only in 80% of the time.

NOTE: Torchio requires 4D (channel, width, height, slice) data. So you'll need to expand a dimension while transforming. Don't forget to squeeze it back to original.

Ex: augmentation(data) should return a transformed tensor with a shape of (C, W, H) where C is channel, W is width and H is height.

import torchio as tio

def augmentation(data):
  ##### START OF YOUR CODE #####
  #Mask list for the transformations.
  mask = []
  #3D to 4D
  data_4d = data.unsqueeze(0)
  #Append the transformations
  mask.append(tio.RandomNoise(p=0.2))
  mask.append(tio.RandomBiasField(p=0.2))
  mask.append(tio.RandomGhosting(p=0.2))
  mask.append(tio.RandomSpike(p=0.2))
  mask.append(tio.RandomAffine(degrees=10, scales=0., translation=0.,p=0.2))
  #Choose a mask and apply it 0.8 of times.
  if random.random()<0.8:
    num_transformations = random.randint(0, (len(mask) - 1))
    chosen_mask = mask[num_transformations]
    masked_data = chosen_mask(data_4d)
    data_3d = masked_data.squeeze(0)
  else:
    data_3d = data_4d.squeeze(0)
  return data_3d
  ##### END OF YOUR CODE #####

V. Create CustomDataset class using the functions above. You need to define 2 more functions in this class.¶

  • __len__(self) > returns the size of the data
  • __getitem__(self, idx) > returns a tuple of image and label

NOTE: Do the necessary modifications to use the function arguments as class attributes for a cleaner code.

In [ ]:
import os
import numpy as np
import torch
from PIL import Image
import torchio as tio
import torchvision.transforms as T


class CustomDataset(torch.utils.data.Dataset):
  def __init__(self, image_size, data_folder, partition):
    ##### START OF YOUR CODE #####
    self.image_size = image_size
    self.data_folder = data_folder
    self.partition = partition
    ##### END OF YOUR CODE #####

  def __len__(self):
    ##### START OF YOUR CODE #####
    return len(self.img_paths())
    ##### END OF YOUR CODE #####

  def __getitem__(self, idx):
    ##### START OF YOUR CODE #####
    image_path = self.img_paths()[idx] #Take the image path
    image = self.read_and_resize_img(image_path) #Read&resize the image

    image = self.augmentation(image) #Augmentation part
    #Set the label either 1 or 0.
    if self.partition == "normal":
      label = 0
    else:
      label = 1
    return image, torch.tensor(label)
    ##### END OF YOUR CODE #####

  def img_paths(self):
    ##### START OF YOUR CODE #####
    partition_paths = os.path.join(self.data_folder, self.partition)
    normal_path = os.path.join(partition_paths, "normal")
    normal_img_paths = [os.path.join(normal_path, filename) for filename in os.listdir(normal_path)]
    covid_path = os.path.join(partition_paths, "covid")
    covid_img_paths = [os.path.join(covid_path, filename) for filename in os.listdir(covid_path)]
    combined_path = normal_img_paths + covid_img_paths
    random.shuffle(combined_path)
    return combined_path

    ##### END OF YOUR CODE #####

  def read_and_resize_img(self, path):
    ##### START OF YOUR CODE #####
    img = Image.open(path)
    img = img.convert('L')
    transform = T.Compose([T.ToTensor()])
    img = transform(img)
    if img.size(0) != image_size or img.size(1) != image_size or img.size(2) != image_size:
          img = T.functional.resize(img, image_size)
    return img
    ##### END OF YOUR CODE #####

  def augmentation(self, data):
    ##### START OF YOUR CODE #####
    mask = []
    data_4d = data.unsqueeze(0)
    mask.append(tio.RandomNoise(p=0.2))
    mask.append(tio.RandomBiasField(p=0.2))
    mask.append(tio.RandomGhosting(p=0.2))
    mask.append(tio.RandomSpike(p=0.2))
    mask.append(tio.RandomAffine(degrees=10, scales=0., translation=0.,p=0.2))
    if random.random()<0.8:
        num_transformations = random.randint(0, (len(mask) - 1))
        chosen_mask = mask[num_transformations]
        masked_data = chosen_mask(data_4d)
        data_3d = masked_data.squeeze(0)
    else:
      data_3d = data_4d.squeeze(0)
    return data_3d
  ##### END OF YOUR CODE #####
